            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Cody Miller\u2019s story is one of trading suburban stability for creative fulfillment. Raised in a quiet Sacramento subdivision, the only child of a pragmatic accountant father and a teacher mother, Cody spent his youth escaping into the digital worlds of video games and early internet animation. His parents supported his hobby but hoped he\u2019d find a more \u201csecure\u201d path. He enrolled in the Digital Media Arts program at San Francisco State University, a compromise that brought him to the city that had always fascinated him from afar.\n\nThe turning point came during his sophomore year. Cody, already more skilled in After Effects than many of his professors, landed a coveted internship at a small but scrappy ad agency in SoMa. Juggling a full course load with demanding client work, he faced a choice. He saw his future not in a classroom, but in a studio. With a guaranteed job offer, he dropped out of college, a decision that caused a rift with his parents but ultimately defined his career. He spent the next decade honing his craft, surviving a dot-com bubble burst that forced him into a successful freelance stint, and eventually climbing the ranks.\n\nToday, at 34, Cody is a Senior Motion Graphics Designer for a popular lifestyle and entertainment company. His $135,000 salary affords him a life his parents now concede is \u201csecure.\u201d He lives in a rent-controlled one-bedroom apartment in the Mission District, a neighborhood whose vibrant, chaotic energy fuels his creativity. His daily 3.8-mile commute on the J-Church line is a ritual of coffee, podcasts, and people-watching.\n\nSocially, Cody is rebuilding after a long-term relationship ended a year ago over the classic SF dilemma: she wanted to move to the suburbs to buy a house, and he couldn't imagine leaving. His circle consists of a tight-knit group of industry friends he meets for beers in Hayes Valley or climbs with at Dogpatch Boulders. He feels deeply connected to San Francisco\u2014a city that rewarded his talent and ambition. His dream isn't management, but creative autonomy: to one day direct a short animated film. His more immediate aspiration is to save enough for a down payment on a small condo, a tangible stake in the city that has become his true home."
        },
        {
            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1.\nHe remembers the phone call to his dad, made from the noisy hallway of his SF State dorm. He explained the job offer, the decision to drop out. The silence on the other end felt heavier than the miles between them. It was the first time he'd heard genuine disappointment in his father's voice. The fear was immense, but beneath it was a thrilling, terrifying certainty. At 19, that conversation was the true start of his adult life, a painful but necessary severing of the path they\u2019d planned for him.\n\n2.\nThe night after she left, the Mission apartment felt cavernous. He sat on the hardwood floor, the only sound a distant siren. On the shared iPad, the Zillow app was still open to three-bedroom houses in Walnut Creek. A profound sadness washed over him, but as he looked out his window at the vibrant chaos of 24th Street, he felt a quiet, stubborn resolve. At 33, he mourned a future lost, but knew he\u2019d chosen the right place to be alone in.\n\n3.\nIt was 2008, and tech was hemorrhaging jobs. He was freelancing, barely scraping by on ramen and anxiety. Then, a check arrived for a motion graphics package he\u2019d poured his soul into. It wasn\u2019t a fortune, but it was enough to cover two months' rent. Holding that piece of paper, he felt a surge of relief that was almost dizzying. At 23, he realized his talent was its own form of security, a currency that held its value even when the market crashed around him.\n\n4.\nOne Tuesday morning, around age 28, his J-Church train stalled just before Dolores Park. The sun was hitting the palm trees, a guy was practicing trumpet on a park bench, and the car was a silent chorus of people absorbed in phones and books. He didn't feel impatient. Instead, a wave of profound contentment hit him. He wasn't just a transplant anymore; he was a piece of this specific, beautiful, everyday scene. The city had finally claimed him, and he had happily surrendered.\n\n5.\nDuring his internship, he pulled an all-nighter for a huge pitch. Around 3 AM, his creative director appeared with greasy al pastor burritos from a nearby taqueria. They ate standing up, watching the final render export. As the sun rose over the Bay Bridge, illuminating their sleep-deprived faces in the monitor's glow, Cody felt an electric sense of belonging. At 19, he knew, with absolute certainty, that this exhaustion, this camaraderie, this creative battle\u2014this was his classroom and his future."
